{"by":"herf","id":47779198,"parent":47776667,"text":"I think HiDPI is another reason - these were from the &quot;96 DPI&quot; era where pixels looked the same on every screen. You can draw all your pixel art at 2x (or 3x) and scale it down at load time, but it&#x27;s not super easy.\nAlso, some of the RAM usage of modern apps is the need for a full backing store for each window - in the &quot;true&quot; win32 days like Windows 95, XP, or Win7 in classic mode, you&#x27;d be drawing directly to the front buffer, with no extra RAM&#x2F;VRAM usage per pixel. Of course it flickered and looked bad, but it was fast and cheap.","time":1776262199,"type":"comment"}